Moreover, Menander had the greatest reverenoe for Euripides, who, in comparison with the other famous tragedians of Greece, shows perhaps the greatest technical skill in the weaving and unravelling of plots. The plots of Euripides abeund in surprises aud complications; and if these are characteristic of the Terentian plays, itis chiefly due to the fact that Menander and the other writers of New Comedy had studied in the school ol Euripides.
